<section>
  <div class="h2-kicker">Deep dives</div>
  <h2>One paragraph per agent</h2>
  <p class="h2-sub">Skim the cards; the verdict line is the punchline.</p>

  <div class="agents">

    <div class="agent-card">
      <h3>opencode</h3>
      <div class="by">by Anomaly (SST team) · MIT · Go</div>
      <div class="stat-row">
        <span class="pill acc">~161k ★</span>
        <span class="pill">TUI · desktop · IDE</span>
        <span class="pill">75+ providers</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        Launched June 2025, opencode broke out by being everything Claude Code is
        — agentic, terminal-native, polished — without being tied to a single
        model vendor. A persistent background server keeps sessions alive across
        SSH drops; it auto-loads the right Language Server so it understands
        types and symbols, not just text.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><b>Built-in agents:</b> <code>build</code> (full access) and <code>plan</code> (read-only).</li>
        <li><b>LSP-aware</b> code understanding out of the box.</li>
        <li>Active daily development; ~6.5M MAUs by Q2 2026.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="verdict"><b>Verdict:</b> the default pick unless you have a strong reason otherwise.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="agent-card">
      <h3>Cline</h3>
      <div class="by">by cline.bot · Apache 2.0 · TypeScript</div>
      <div class="stat-row">
        <span class="pill acc">~61k ★</span>
        <span class="pill">VS Code · JetBrains · Zed · Neovim</span>
        <span class="pill">v3.83</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        Originally "Claude Dev" — still the safest IDE-native agent. Plan/Act
        mode forces structured review before destructive changes; computer use
        lets it verify UI work in a real browser; <code>.clinerules/</code>
        turns coding standards into versioned, file-scoped governance. The MCP
        marketplace plus 30+ providers means real flexibility.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><b>Spend limits</b>, YOLO and Lazy Teammate modes to tune autonomy.</li>
        <li><b>Puppeteer-driven browser</b> for UI verification.</li>
        <li>Now also ships an SDK and preview CLI.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="verdict"><b>Verdict:</b> the default if VS Code is your home.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="agent-card">
      <h3>OpenHands</h3>
      <div class="by">by All-Hands-AI · MIT · Python</div>
      <div class="stat-row">
        <span class="pill acc">~75k ★</span>
        <span class="pill">Web · headless · cloud</span>
        <span class="pill good">~72% SWE-bench Verified</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        The "open Devin." Runs an autonomous loop inside a sandboxed runtime
        (Docker by default) that plans, edits, runs commands, and iterates on
        long tasks. Model-flexible by design — Claude Opus for quality, GPT-5 for
        speed, Ollama for privacy. The first-party OpenHands Index benchmark is
        becoming a real reference point alongside SWE-bench.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><b>Best-in-class agentic loop</b> for end-to-end issue resolution.</li>
        <li>Headless mode for CI / batch automation.</li>
        <li>Enterprise dir is non-MIT; core is fully open.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="verdict"><b>Verdict:</b> what to pick when "fix this whole issue" is the prompt.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="agent-card">
      <h3>Aider</h3>
      <div class="by">by Aider-AI (Paul Gauthier) · Apache 2.0 · Python</div>
      <div class="stat-row">
        <span class="pill acc">~39k ★</span>
        <span class="pill">Terminal</span>
        <span class="pill">100+ languages</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        The original. Git-native to its core: every change becomes an atomic
        commit with a sensible message, so <code>git</code> is your undo button.
        Architect mode pairs a reasoning model (e.g. Opus) with a faster
        executor; watch mode lets you scatter <code># AI: …</code> markers
        across files and have them implemented in place. Voice in, images
        in, lints + tests run automatically.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><b>Repo map</b> using tree-sitter for large codebases.</li>
        <li><b>Architect/editor split</b> for cheap, controllable iteration.</li>
        <li>Best workflow for changes that are small, frequent, reviewable.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="verdict"><b>Verdict:</b> still the cleanest terminal pair-programmer if git discipline matters.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="agent-card">
      <h3>Roo Code</h3>
      <div class="by">by Roo Veterinary Inc. · Apache 2.0 · TypeScript</div>
      <div class="stat-row">
        <span class="pill acc">~25k ★</span>
        <span class="pill">VS Code (+ Cloud)</span>
        <span class="pill">Cline fork</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        Forked from Cline and built around explicit "modes" — Code, Architect,
        Ask, Debug, plus user-defined personas with scoped tool permissions
        (security auditor, TS migration assistant, docs writer, …). Context is
        opt-in via <code>@file</code>/<code>@dir</code>, which keeps the agent
        from sprawling.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><b>Custom modes + mode gallery</b> as the central abstraction.</li>
        <li>Optional Roo Code Cloud for GitHub/Slack-triggered runs.</li>
        <li>More configurable than Cline; slightly steeper learning curve.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="verdict"><b>Verdict:</b> pick over Cline if you want specialized personas, not one agent.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="agent-card">
      <h3>Kilo Code</h3>
      <div class="by">by Kilo-Org · Apache 2.0 · TypeScript</div>
      <div class="stat-row">
        <span class="pill acc">~20k ★</span>
        <span class="pill">VS Code · JetBrains · CLI</span>
        <span class="pill">500+ models</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        Also descended from the Cline/Roo lineage but pushed toward an
        "all-in-one platform": Architect/Coder/Debugger modes, an MCP server
        marketplace, and a hosted router that exposes 500+ models at
        pass-through pricing (no markup). #1 on OpenRouter by traffic.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><b>JetBrains support</b> since Sept 2025 (IntelliJ, PyCharm, …).</li>
        <li>Polished onboarding, good for teams that want one tool everywhere.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="verdict"><b>Verdict:</b> the "buy one tool, get every model" option.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="agent-card">
      <h3>Goose</h3>
      <div class="by">originally Block, now AAIF / Linux Foundation · Apache 2.0 · Rust</div>
      <div class="stat-row">
        <span class="pill acc">~20k ★</span>
        <span class="pill">Desktop · CLI · API</span>
        <span class="pill">70+ MCP extensions</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        Born inside Block, donated to the new Agentic AI Foundation. Goose is
        deliberately local-first: the agent runs on your machine and only your
        chosen LLM provider sees prompts. Recent releases added
        <code>goose serve</code> (background daemon), Gemini OAuth, Copilot ACP
        provider, and an egress-logging inspector for governance.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><b>Foundation-governed</b> — useful for enterprises wary of vendor capture.</li>
        <li><b>Strong MCP extension ecosystem</b> across DBs, APIs, browsers.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="verdict"><b>Verdict:</b> the "boring, well-governed" choice for serious infra teams.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="agent-card">
      <h3>Continue.dev</h3>
      <div class="by">by continuedev · Apache 2.0 · TypeScript</div>
      <div class="stat-row">
        <span class="pill acc">~30k ★</span>
        <span class="pill">VS Code · JetBrains · CI</span>
        <span class="pill">Continue Hub</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        The longest-running OSS IDE assistant. In 2026 the pitch shifted toward
        "quality control for your software factory" — Continue now runs review
        agents inside CI on every PR, in addition to the chat/edit/autocomplete
        in the IDE. Every layer can point at a local endpoint (Ollama, vLLM,
        on-prem); telemetry is one flag.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><b>CI/PR review agent</b> is the unique 2026 capability.</li>
        <li>Continue Hub for shared prompts and configs across a team.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="verdict"><b>Verdict:</b> best when "AI also reviews PRs" is part of the requirement.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="agent-card">
      <h3>SWE-agent</h3>
      <div class="by">by Princeton + Stanford · MIT · Python</div>
      <div class="stat-row">
        <span class="pill acc">~19k ★</span>
        <span class="pill">CLI / script</span>
        <span class="pill">NeurIPS 2024</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        Less product, more research scaffold. SWE-agent's contribution is the
        Agent-Computer Interface — an abstraction of "what tools an LLM should
        see." The 1.0 release plus Claude 3.7 hit SOTA on SWE-bench at the time;
        also widely used for CTFs and offensive security exercises.
        <code>mini-swe-agent</code> is a 100-line variant that still scores
        &gt;74% on SWE-bench Verified.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>The right starting point if you want to <b>build</b> an agent, not use one.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="verdict"><b>Verdict:</b> for benchmarking, research, and security work — not daily coding.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="agent-card">
      <h3>Plandex</h3>
      <div class="by">by plandex-ai · MIT · Go</div>
      <div class="stat-row">
        <span class="pill acc">~15k ★</span>
        <span class="pill">Terminal</span>
        <span class="pill">2M token context</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        Built for the case where the task spans dozens of files and dies on
        any normal agent. Plandex maintains a cumulative diff sandbox so AI
        changes stay separate from your tree until you accept them; tree-sitter
        project maps let it index ~20M tokens of repo. Mixes Anthropic, OpenAI,
        Google and OSS models per role.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><b>Sandboxed diffs</b> make multi-step changes much safer to review.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="verdict"><b>Verdict:</b> reach for it on "rewrite the auth subsystem"-size tasks.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="agent-card">
      <h3>Codex CLI</h3>
      <div class="by">by OpenAI · Apache 2.0 · Rust</div>
      <div class="stat-row">
        <span class="pill acc">~76k ★</span>
        <span class="pill">Terminal</span>
        <span class="pill warn">OpenAI models only</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        OpenAI's answer to Claude Code: a Rust-built terminal agent with both
        an interactive TUI and an <code>exec</code> mode for scripting. Ships
        a dedicated review subcommand, MCP support, subagents for parallel
        work, image generation, and resumable transcripts. Open source — but
        only useful if you're paying OpenAI.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Worth knowing even if you don't use it — many ideas leak across agents.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="verdict"><b>Verdict:</b> first pick if your stack is GPT-5/Codex; otherwise opencode wins on flexibility.</div>
    </div>

  </div>
</section>

<section>
  <div class="h2-kicker">Choosing</div>
  <h2>By scenario</h2>
  <p class="h2-sub">Match the situation to the agent, instead of the other way around.</p>

  <div class="picker">
    <div class="row">
      <div class="q">Solo dev, terminal-first, want one tool</div>
      <div class="a">opencode</div>
      <div class="why">Provider-agnostic, sessions survive everything, LSP-aware. No reason to pick anything else as a starting point.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="q">You live inside VS Code</div>
      <div class="a">Cline → graduate to Roo Code</div>
      <div class="why">Start with Cline for the broadest doc/community footprint; move to Roo Code if you want specialized "modes" per task.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="q">You want an agent to fix issues end-to-end</div>
      <div class="a">OpenHands</div>
      <div class="why">Sandboxed runtime + best public SWE-bench numbers among OSS agents. Pair it with Claude or local Ollama.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="q">Git discipline is non-negotiable</div>
      <div class="a">Aider</div>
      <div class="why">Atomic commits per change, architect/editor split, lints + tests run automatically. <code>git</code> is your safety net.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="q">Privacy-sensitive enterprise, local models only</div>
      <div class="a">Goose or Continue.dev</div>
      <div class="why">Both run end-to-end against local endpoints. Goose has stronger governance hooks; Continue has CI integration.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="q">Massive multi-file refactor</div>
      <div class="a">Plandex</div>
      <div class="why">2M-token plans + cumulative diff sandbox are designed exactly for "rewrite this subsystem" tasks.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="q">You're building your own agent or doing research</div>
      <div class="a">SWE-agent (or mini-swe-agent)</div>
      <div class="why">Smallest, cleanest scaffold; ACI abstraction is genuinely useful to study.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="q">All-OpenAI shop</div>
      <div class="a">Codex CLI</div>
      <div class="why">Tightest integration with OpenAI models; review subcommand and subagents are polished.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section>
  <div class="h2-kicker">What changed</div>
  <h2>Notes on the field in 2026</h2>
  <div class="notes-grid">
    <div class="note" data-cf-change="ch-research-pick" style="border-left-color: var(--accent); background: linear-gradient(180deg, rgba(124,242,196,0.08), transparent);">
      <b>Best for research: SWE-agent.</b> If your goal is benchmarking,
      studying agent architectures, or building your own — start with
      <a href="https://github.com/SWE-agent/SWE-agent">SWE-agent</a> (Princeton/Stanford,
      NeurIPS 2024). It's the cleanest scaffold, its Agent-Computer Interface
      abstraction is genuinely instructive, and
      <a href="https://github.com/SWE-agent/mini-swe-agent">mini-swe-agent</a> is
      ~100 lines of Python that still scores &gt;74% on SWE-bench Verified — an
      ideal base to hack on. OpenHands is a close second for reproducibility
      work (well-documented, sandboxed runtime, its own OpenHands Index
      benchmark), and Aider is worth studying for repo-map / tree-sitter
      context techniques.
    </div>
    <div class="note">
      <b>Terminal agents won 2025.</b> Cursor-style IDE forks are still
      popular, but the breakout growth this past year was all terminal-native
      (opencode, Codex CLI, Claude Code). The reason is simple: terminals
      compose with everything else developers already do.
    </div>
    <div class="note">
      <b>MCP became table stakes.</b> Every serious agent listed here either
      supports MCP today or shipped it within the last six months. If a tool
      doesn't, it's at a structural disadvantage for integrations.
    </div>
    <div class="note">
      <b>"Modes" are the new abstraction.</b> Roo Code, Kilo, opencode and
      Cline all converged on a plan/build/debug split. Specialized personas
      with scoped tools beat one general-purpose agent for most real tasks.
    </div>
    <div class="note">
      <b>SWE-bench got saturated.</b> Verified is now &gt;90% on the frontier;
      OpenHands launched its own broader Index (issue resolution + frontend +
      greenfield + testing + info gathering) as a replacement reference.
    </div>
    <div class="note">
      <b>Google withdrew Gemini CLI's free tier.</b> The open-source repo lives
      on, but as of June 18 2026 free use ends; Google is steering users to
      Antigravity CLI. Excluded from the main table because of the disruption,
      worth mentioning.
    </div>
    <div class="note">
      <b>Foundations are starting to matter.</b> Goose moved from Block to the
      Linux Foundation's Agentic AI Foundation. Expect more "neutral home"
      moves as enterprises ask harder questions about vendor capture.
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section>
  <div class="h2-kicker">References</div>
  <h2>Sources</h2>
